# ─── Render-hosted legacy pages (proxied, not SPA-routed) ─────────────
# The extension marketing page, the extension self-register flow and the
# .vsix download all live in the Render backend (public/*.html). When a
# visitor hits these paths on vajbagent.netlify.app the default SPA
# fallback below would load the React app with "extenzija" as a route,
# which React doesn't know — so the user ends up on the home screen
# "Šta želiš da napraviš?" instead of the Cursor extension landing page.
#
# A 200 rewrite proxies the response from Render without changing the
# browser URL, so Netlify visitors see the same content as vajbagent.com
# and there's still a single source of truth.
/extenzija              https://vajbagent.com/extenzija               200
/extenzija/             https://vajbagent.com/extenzija               200
/dashboard              https://vajbagent.com/dashboard               200
/dashboard/*            https://vajbagent.com/dashboard/:splat        200
/vajbagent-latest.vsix  https://vajbagent.com/vajbagent-latest.vsix   200
/og-image.png           https://vajbagent.com/og-image.png            200
# Screenshots and other image assets referenced by extenzija.html
# (e.g. /img/screenshots/ss-chat.png). Without this, the SPA fallback
# returns index.html for every image request → broken placeholders.
/img/*                  https://vajbagent.com/img/:splat              200

# Preview paths must be handled by the in-browser Service Worker.
# If the SW isn't active yet (first visit, not controlling, disabled, etc.),
# serving /__vajb_preview/... via the SPA fallback would load our entire
# React app inside the preview iframe, which then fails with CORS noise
# because the iframe is sandboxed to a null origin. Return 404 instead
# so the preview layer knows to retry/fall back to blob mode.
/__vajb_preview/*  /preview-unavailable.html  404

# Default SPA fallback for the main app.
/*    /index.html   200
